## Project Structure

```
VQE/
├── src/
│   └── quantum.qs       # Q# ansatz and general expectation value
├── hamiltonian.py        # PySCF + OpenFermion Hamiltonian pipeline
├── interface.py          # Cost function, optimizer, run_vqe()
├── qsharp.json           # Q# project config
└── README.md
```

---

## How It Works

```
Molecule geometry
      ↓
PySCF Hartree-Fock     → molecular integrals
      ↓
Jordan-Wigner transform → Pauli string with coefficients
      ↓
Q# ansatz circuit       → parameterised quantum state |ψ(θ)⟩
      ↓
Expectation values      → ⟨ψ(θ)|H|ψ(θ)⟩ per Pauli term
      ↓
COBYLA optimizer        → minimise energy over θ
      ↓
Ground state energy E₀
```

---

## Requirements

```
qsharp
pyscf
openfermion
openfermionpyscf
numpy
scipy
```

Install inside a virtual environment (Linux/WSL recommended for PySCF):
```bash
python3 -m venv vqe-env
source vqe-env/bin/activate
pip install qsharp pyscf openfermion openfermionpyscf numpy scipy
```

---

## Results

H₂ ground state energy (STO-3G basis):
- Exact HF: -1.1175 Hartree
- This VQE: -1.1077 Hartree
- Difference: ~0.01 Hartree (shot noise limited)

---

## Known Limitations

- Accuracy is shot-noise limited — more shots improve results but increase runtime
- Ansatz expressibility limits accuracy for larger molecules — more layers needed
- Simulator only — not tested on real quantum hardware
- Runtime scales with molecule size and number of Pauli terms

---

Built with Q# (Microsoft Quantum), PySCF, and OpenFermion.